PSEUDOCODE
==========

Define two modes: BLINK_MODE, BREATHE_MODE
Current mode = BLINK_MODE

Initialize SysTick -> 1ms timebase
Initialize PA5 as GPIO output (for blink mode)
Initialize PC13 as input with pull-up (Button)
Initialize EXTI on PC13 falling edge -> EXTI4_15 IRQ

In EXTI ISR:
    Clear FPR1 flag
    Set mode_changed flag = 1
    Toggle current_mode (BLINK <-> BREATHE)

In main loop:

    If mode_changed flag is set:
        Clear mode_changed flag
        Debounce wait via ms_ticks (20ms)
        If mode is now BREATHE:
            Reconfigure PA5 as AF2 (TIM2_CH1)
            Start PWM on TIM2
        If mode is now BLINK:
            Stop TIM2
            Reconfigure PA5 as GPIO output
            Set LED OFF cleanly

    If BLINK_MODE:
        Non-blocking toggle every 500ms via ms_ticks

    If BREATHE_MODE:
        Non-blocking duty ramp via ms_ticks
        Update CCR1 each STEP_INTERVAL

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA5   ->  GPIO output (blink mode) / TIM2_CH1 AF2 (breathe mode)
PC13  ->  Onboard User Button  - Active LOW, falling edge triggers EXTI

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Switching MODER while TIM2 is still running. If we reconfigure PA5 back to
  GPIO output without first stopping TIM2 (CR1 &= ~CEN) and disabling the
  channel (CCER &= ~CC1E), the timer peripheral still drives the pin through the
  alternate function path even after MODER is changed back. Always disable the
  peripheral before reconfiguring the pin. pa5_set_gpio_output() handles this in
  the correct order.

* Acting on is_mode_changed directly inside the ISR. Switching pin modes,
  stopping timers, and calling functions with loops inside an ISR is
  dangerous. The ISR here only sets two flags and exits. All the heavy
  transition work happens in the main loop where it is safe, interruptible, and
  has access to ms_ticks for debouncing.

* `now` snapshot going stale after debounce wait. After the blocking debounce
  wait inside is_mode_changed handling, now holds an old value. That is why
  `last` are reset using fresh ms_ticks reads after the transition, not
  `now`. Otherwise the blink or breathe timer appears to fire immediately.

* Breathe state not reset on mode switch. If we switch back to breathe mode
  mid-cycle without resetting `duty` and is_ramp_up, the ramp resumes from
  wherever it left off, sometimes at full brightness going downward, which looks
  like a glitch. Always reset breathe state on each entry into breathe mode.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* The ISR-sets-flag, main-loop-acts pattern. This is the single most important
  architectural pattern in bare-metal firmware. The ISR is a trip wire, it
  detects the event, records it minimally, and gets out. The main loop is the
  worker, it sees the flag, does the heavy lifting safely. From this program
  onwards it is the default approach.

* Dynamic pin reconfiguration. Switching a pin between GPIO and alternate
  function at runtime is perfectly valid. Motor controllers switch between PWM
  drive and GPIO brake. Communication peripherals switch between SPI and GPIO
  for bit-banging fallback. The key rule is always: disable the peripheral
  first, reconfigure the pin, then re-enable.

* This program is the complexity ceiling for GPIO/TIM2. Everything from here
  shifts focus to new peripherals: UART, ADC, DMA, RTC. The non-blocking loop
  structure, ISR flag pattern, and mode-switching technique established here
  carry forward unchanged into every remaining program.
